eased production of melanin pigment"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccumulation of toxic galactose metabolites\u003C/strong\u003E. Galactosemia is caused by deficiency of galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase, which leads to accumulation of galactose and its metabolites. These accumulated substances are toxic to tissues, particularly affecting the liver, brain, and eyes. This represents the first major consequence of enzyme defects: accumulation of substrate to toxic levels when a metabolic pathway is blocked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailure to inactivate neutrophil elastase\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the pathophysiology of \u03b11-antitrypsin deficiency, which leads to pulmonary emphysema. This represents the third major consequence of enzyme defects: failure to inactivate a tissue-damaging substrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive production of feedback inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a recognised major consequence of enzyme defects. While altered feedback inhibition can occur in some disorders, it is not the primary mechanism in galactosemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to degrade complex lipids in lysosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the pathophysiology of certain lysosomal storage diseases, such as Gaucher disease or Tay-Sachs disease, which result from deficiencies in specific lysosomal enzymes. While these also involve substrate accumulation, they specifically affect lysosomal degradation of complex lipids, which is not the case in galactosemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased production of melanin pigment\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the pathophysiology of albinism, which results from tyrosinase deficiency. Tyrosinase is necessary for biosynthesis of melanin from tyrosine. This represents the second major consequence of enzyme defects: decreased amount of an essential end product.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGalactosemia represents a classic example of the first pathophysiological consequence of enzyme defects, where the block in metabolism leads to accumulation of the substrate (galactose) and related metabolites to toxic levels, resulting in tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Enzyme defects can lead to three major consequences: accumulation of substrate, decreased end product, or failure to inactivate a tissue-damaging substrate.","Galactosemia is caused by galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase deficiency, leading to accumulation of toxic galactose metabolites.","Lysosomal storage diseases result from deficiency of degradative enzymes leading to accumulation of complex substrates within lysosomes."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 147-148"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81001"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20880"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81001"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-15T15:52:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-15T15:52:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13755"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98597"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{